<main>
    <div class="trees-content">
        <div class="trees-text">
            <h2>Trees</h2>
            <p>A tree is a hierarchical, non-linear data structure consisting of nodes connected by edges. It starts with a root node and extends into subtrees of children nodes. For more information, visit <a href="https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/all-you-need-to-know-about-tree-data-structures-bceacb85490c/" target="_blank">this guide on tree data structures</a>.</p>
            <h3>Types of Trees:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Binary Tree:</strong> Each node has at most two children.</li>
                <li><strong>Binary Search Tree (BST):</strong> A binary tree where left child nodes have lesser value, and right child nodes have greater value than their parent.</li>
                <li><strong>Heap:</strong> A specialized tree-based structure satisfying the heap property.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Applications:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Hierarchical Data Storage:</strong> File systems, organizational structures.</li>
                <li><strong>Searching and Sorting:</strong> Binary search trees for efficient searching.</li>
                <li><strong>Parser Implementation:</strong> Syntax trees in compilers.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="trees-image">
            <img src="img/Tree.png" alt="Trees Example">
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="graphs-content">
        <div class="graphs-text">
            <h2>Graphs</h2>
            <p>A graph is a collection of nodes (vertices) connected by edges. It can model various complex structures. For more information, visit <a href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/introduction-to-graphs-data-structure-and-algorithm-tutorials/" target="_blank">this introduction to graphs</a>.</p>
            <h3>Types of Graphs:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Directed Graph (Digraph):</strong> Edges have a direction, indicating a one-way relationship.</li>
                <li><strong>Undirected Graph:</strong> Edges are bidirectional.</li>
                <li><strong>Weighted Graph:</strong> Edges carry weights representing cost, distance, or any quantitative measure.</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Applications:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Networking:</strong> Represents computer networks and social networks.</li>
                <li><strong>Transportation:</strong> Models routes in maps for GPS navigation.</li>
                <li><strong>Algorithm Implementation:</strong> Used in algorithms like Dijkstra's for shortest path finding.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="graphs-image">
            <img src="img/graph.png" alt="Graphs Example">
        </div>
    </div>
